184–1221","1259":"1259","Bef 28 Jul 1221":"before 28 July 1221","1233":"1233","1221":"1221","1165":"1165","about 1200":"about 1200","1184":"1184","1283":"1283","Abt 1208":"about 1208","about 1221":"about 1221","1208":"1208","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England","England":"England, United Kingdom","Milton Keynes, Buckinghamshire, England":"Milton Keynes, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Keynes","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Caines  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Caines","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Cahaignes in Eure, France, or Cahaynes in Calvados, France, both probably named with a Celtic element meaning ‘juniper bush’."]}]},{"name":"Lucas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["In part a learned form of   Luke  , in part a transferred use of the surname derived from it in the Middle Ages. The Latin form <i>Lucas</i> was often used in the Middle Ages in written documents in place of the spoken vernacular form <i>Luke</i>, hence the common surname. It is also the spelling preferred in the Authorized Version of the New Testament, which has had some influence on its selection as a given name. There has been a sharp rise in its popularity since the turn of the century. <i>Lucas</i> is now also used as an Anglicized form of various Eastern European equivalents (  see the cognates listed at  Luke  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Luke","meanings":["Middle English vernacular form of   Lucas  , Latin form of the post-classical Greek name <i>Loukas</i> ‘man from Lucania’. This owes its perennial popularity throughout Christian Europe to the fact that, from the 2nd century onwards, the third gospel in the New Testament has been ascribed to the Lucas or Luke mentioned at various places in Acts and in the Epistles. Little is known about him beyond the facts that he was a doctor, a Gentile, and a friend and convert of St Paul. The name was borne by the character  Luke Skywalker  in the film Star Wars (  1977 ), and rose sharply in popularity in the 1990s."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Lucas de Keynes was born about 1208, in England, United Kingdom, his father, Hugh de Keynes, was 45 and his mother, Amabel de Bereville, was 25. He had at least 1 son. He died in 1259, in Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 52."},"et":{"Abt 1208–1259":"umbes 1208–1259","1208–1221":"1208–1221","1208–1259":"1208–1259","1233–1283":"1233–1283","1165–1221":"1165–1221","1184–1221":"1184–1221","1259":"1259","Bef 28 Jul 1221":"enne 28. juulit 1221","1233":"1233","1221":"1221","1165":"1165","about 1200":"umbes 1200","1184":"1184","1283":"1283","Abt 1208":"umbes 1208","about 1221":"umbes 1221","1208":"1208","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Milton Keynes, Buckinghamshire, England":"Milton Keynes, Buckinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1208–1259":"noin 1208–1259","1208–1221":"1208–1221","1208–1259":"1208–1259","1233–1283":"1233–1283","1165–1221":"1165–1221","1184–1221":"1184–1221","1259":"1259","Bef 28 Jul 1221":"ennen vuo